1
00:00:09,720 --> 00:00:11,480
There's no way out of this.

2
00:00:11,560 --> 00:00:13,000
We're going to die here.

3
00:00:13,720 --> 00:00:15,240
DOCTOR: Pass me the vibro-cutters.

4
00:00:15,360 --> 00:00:16,560
CLARA: They're in my pocket.

5
00:00:16,800 --> 00:00:18,160
DOCTOR: Come on, then, pass them to me.

6
00:00:18,240 --> 00:00:20,560
In my other jacket. At home.

7
00:00:20,640 --> 00:00:23,000
Why have you got have two jackets?
Is one of them faulty?

8
00:00:23,080 --> 00:00:25,600
Look, I don't have the vibro-cutters.
If I had the vibro-cutters,

9
00:00:25,680 --> 00:00:28,080
I wouldn't be able to pass you
the vibro-cutters.

10
00:00:28,160 --> 00:00:29,800
We're going to starve
to death out here.

11
00:00:30,040 --> 00:00:31,640
Of course we won't starve.

12
00:00:31,760 --> 00:00:34,560
The sand piranhas will get us
long before that.

13
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:39,520
Hiya. Sorry I'm late.

14
00:00:39,840 --> 00:00:42,240
You're not, but you are brown.
You're very brown.

15
00:00:42,320 --> 00:00:43,720
You weren't that brown this morning.

16
00:00:43,840 --> 00:00:46,000
Sunbed. Phew!
I'll get them in. Usual?

17
00:00:47,040 --> 00:00:48,360
DOCTOR: Fish people.

18
00:00:48,440 --> 00:00:49,600
CLARA: What are they like?

19
00:00:49,680 --> 00:00:52,400
Fish and people. Come and see.

20
00:00:54,520 --> 00:00:57,440
-How's you?
-Evening. Nice frock.

21
00:00:57,520 --> 00:00:59,440
-It's a bit wet.
-Freak shower.

22
00:01:02,080 --> 00:01:03,120
Was that seaweed?

23
00:01:03,680 --> 00:01:04,720
I said freak.

24
00:01:08,520 --> 00:01:09,600
How much further?

25
00:01:09,680 --> 00:01:11,520
The Tardis has got to be
around this corner.

26
00:01:11,600 --> 00:01:12,600
-Oh!
-Oh!

27
00:01:12,720 --> 00:01:14,600
I hate soldiers.
Don't you hate soldiers?

28
00:01:14,680 --> 00:01:15,680
Yeah.

29
00:01:15,760 --> 00:01:16,880
-DOCTOR: Just keep running!
-Ooh!

30
00:01:19,160 --> 00:01:22,880
-Oh, yeah. Danny. Hiya.
-Morning. Ready to run?

31
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:24,040
Mmm-hmm.

32
00:01:24,600 --> 00:01:26,360
(PANTING)

33
00:01:28,920 --> 00:01:31,680
I can't keep doing this. I can't do it.

34
00:01:32,880 --> 00:01:36,320
Yes, I can. I can do it,
of course I can do it.

35
00:01:38,400 --> 00:01:40,400
I've got it all under control.

36
00:01:41,560 --> 00:01:43,240
So, where are we off to?

37
00:01:43,840 --> 00:01:46,840
Clara. You look lovely today.
Have you had a wash?

38
00:01:49,440 --> 00:01:51,880
-Why are you being nice?
-Because it works on you.

39
00:01:51,960 --> 00:01:56,040
Listen, I'm sorry but there's
going to be no trip today.

40
00:01:56,200 --> 00:01:58,920
I'm sorry. Er, I've got to do
a thing. It might take a while.

41
00:01:59,360 --> 00:02:01,040
-What thing?
-Just a thing.

42
00:02:01,400 --> 00:02:04,320
You're being mysterious
and do you know what means?

43
00:02:04,560 --> 00:02:05,920
I'm a man of mystery.

44
00:02:06,080 --> 00:02:08,880
Hmm. It means that you are
a very clever man

45
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:11,240
making the mistake,
common to very clever people,

46
00:02:11,320 --> 00:02:13,880
of assuming that
everybody else is stupid.

47
00:02:13,960 --> 00:02:14,960
Where are you going?

48
00:02:15,120 --> 00:02:17,040
Undercover. Deep cover.

49
00:02:17,200 --> 00:02:18,560
-Can you do deep cover?
-What do you mean?

50
00:02:18,640 --> 00:02:20,640
-Have you seen you?
-Of course I can do deep cover!

51
00:02:20,720 --> 00:02:22,520
(LAUGHING) Where? The Magic Circle?

52
00:02:22,600 --> 00:02:24,080
(SNAPPING FINGERS)

53
00:02:24,160 --> 00:02:26,600
-I'll see you when I see you.
-(SNAPPING FINGERS) When's that?

54
00:02:27,800 --> 00:02:28,880
(SNAPPING FINGERS)

55
00:02:28,960 --> 00:02:30,200
When I see you.

56
00:02:31,960 --> 00:02:32,960
Hmm...

57
00:02:36,720 --> 00:02:37,720
Hmm...

58
00:02:38,960 --> 00:02:40,680
I'LL be sure to have a wash.

59
00:02:40,840 --> 00:02:42,800
Excellent. I was meaning to bring it up.

60
00:02:53,760 --> 00:02:55,280
(MONITOR BEEPING)

61
00:02:58,080 --> 00:02:59,440
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

62
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:02,600
You lot! Not here. Over there.

63
00:03:05,440 --> 00:03:06,800
Morning, Mr Pink.

64
00:03:06,880 --> 00:03:10,040
Morning, Courtney.
And good morning, Miss Oswald.

65
00:03:10,120 --> 00:03:11,760
Morning, Mr Pink.

66
00:03:12,240 --> 00:03:13,240
(GIGGLING)

67
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:19,320
-Do they know?
-Possibly. They're children.

68
00:03:19,720 --> 00:03:22,400
It's like they've got
minds of their own. Are you okay?

69
00:03:22,480 --> 00:03:24,640
Yeah, of course I'm okay.
Why wouldn't I be okay?

70
00:03:24,720 --> 00:03:26,600
I don't know. Every time I see you,
it's like you're...

71
00:03:26,680 --> 00:03:27,720
What?

72
00:03:27,800 --> 00:03:29,880
In a rush. In a state.

73
00:03:29,960 --> 00:03:31,720
In a space helmet one time.

74
00:03:31,800 --> 00:03:34,280
Sorry, er, I've had a thing

75
00:03:34,360 --> 00:03:37,080
and, er, the thing's gone.
So I'm all yours.

76
00:03:37,160 --> 00:03:39,000
-What thing? What's gone?
-Nothing.

77
00:03:39,080 --> 00:03:41,240
It's like you're trying
to be mysterious.

78
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:43,280
I'm not stupid, you know.

79
00:03:44,240 --> 00:03:47,280
(SIGHING)
The next few days are all about you.

80
00:03:47,560 --> 00:03:48,760
I promise.

81
00:03:50,120 --> 00:03:51,120
(CLEARING THROAT)

82
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:56,080
Which means, Jo, you'll have to
cover for 8-4M in L3.

83
00:03:56,520 --> 00:03:58,760
Hold on, there is just one more thing.

84
00:03:58,840 --> 00:04:01,240
Atif's off sick, so we've got a newbie.

85
00:04:01,320 --> 00:04:02,360
I did ask him to come along.

86
00:04:02,440 --> 00:04:04,440
-(KNOCKING)
-Ah, here he is.

87
00:04:06,440 --> 00:04:07,440
Do come in.

88
00:04:09,200 --> 00:04:12,040
I'm the new caretaker. John Smith.

89
00:04:12,560 --> 00:04:14,360
Welcome to Coal Hill, Mr Smith.

90
00:04:14,440 --> 00:04:17,200
Thanks. Yes, John Smith's the name.

91
00:04:17,280 --> 00:04:21,160
But you know, here's the thing.
Most people just call me the Doctor.

92
00:04:22,440 --> 00:04:24,040
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

93
00:05:01,120 --> 00:05:04,040
So if anybody needs me,
just, you know, give me a shout.

94
00:05:04,120 --> 00:05:07,160
I'll be in the storeroom
just getting the lie of the land.

95
00:05:07,240 --> 00:05:10,280
Yes, nobody's taking
any notice at all.

96
00:05:10,400 --> 00:05:12,800
Absolutely good news, because

97
00:05:12,880 --> 00:05:15,600
it means that I must be coming across
just as an absolutely

98
00:05:15,680 --> 00:05:18,240
-boring human being like you.
-(MOUTHING)

99
00:05:18,880 --> 00:05:20,880
Deep cover. Deep cover.

100
00:05:23,120 --> 00:05:25,000
-Do you know him?
-Know who?

101
00:05:25,240 --> 00:05:28,400
-The caretaker, Smith. The Doctor.
-Never seen him before in my life.

102
00:05:28,480 --> 00:05:31,280
Bit intense-looking.
Did you see those eyebrows?

103
00:05:31,400 --> 00:05:32,400
Did he wink at you?

104
00:05:32,480 --> 00:05:34,480
No, I think that was just
sort of like a general wink.

105
00:05:34,560 --> 00:05:36,840
You know, he winked at everybody.
It was a general welcoming wink.

106
00:05:36,920 --> 00:05:39,600
Ah! I have, erm, left some marking.

107
00:05:39,680 --> 00:05:42,720
Assembly. Chop-chop. Off you pop.
Catch you in a bit. Excuse me.

108
00:05:48,120 --> 00:05:50,480
-So, you recognised me, then.
-You're wearing a different coat.

109
00:05:50,560 --> 00:05:54,280
-You saw straight through that.
-Deep cover in my school? Why?

110
00:05:54,360 --> 00:05:56,160
Where's Atif?
What have you done with him?

111
00:05:56,240 --> 00:05:58,680
He's fine, hypnotised,
he thinks he's got the flu.

112
00:05:58,760 --> 00:06:01,800
Also, a flying car and three wives.
It's going to be a rude awakening.

113
00:06:01,880 --> 00:06:03,200
Is it aliens?

114
00:06:03,600 --> 00:06:06,240
Oh, my God, is that
why you're here? Are there aliens?

115
00:06:06,320 --> 00:06:08,520
It's assembly, you better get going.
Go and worship something.

116
00:06:08,600 --> 00:06:10,440
Are the aliens in this school?

117
00:06:10,520 --> 00:06:13,360
Listen, it's lovely talking to you,
but I've really got to get on.

118
00:06:13,440 --> 00:06:14,880
I'm a caretaker now.
Look, I've got a brush.

119
00:06:14,960 --> 00:06:16,880
Doctor, is there an alien
in this school?

120
00:06:16,960 --> 00:06:19,320
Yes, me. Now, go.

121
00:06:19,560 --> 00:06:21,960
The walls need sponging
and there's a sinister puddle.

122
00:06:22,040 --> 00:06:23,120
You can't do this.

123
00:06:23,520 --> 00:06:27,160
You cannot pass yourself off
as a real person among actual people.

124
00:06:27,240 --> 00:06:29,040
I lived among otters
once for a month.

125
00:06:29,120 --> 00:06:31,840
Well, I sulked. River and I,
we had this big fight...

126
00:06:31,920 --> 00:06:35,920
-Human beings are not otters!
-Exactly, it'll be even easier.

127
00:06:37,040 --> 00:06:41,800
Okay. One question.
And you will answer this question.

128
00:06:44,040 --> 00:06:45,080
Are the kids safe?

129
00:06:45,520 --> 00:06:47,720
No. Nobody is safe.

130
00:06:48,120 --> 00:06:51,440
But soon the answer will be
yes, everybody is safe,

131
00:06:51,560 --> 00:06:54,480
if you let me get on now.

132
00:06:55,360 --> 00:06:58,480
Pretend you don't know me.
Stay out of my way.

133
00:06:58,560 --> 00:07:01,440
The less you know, the better.
I'll explain it all later.

134
00:07:01,520 --> 00:07:03,360
-Go and sing with the otters.
-I hate you.

135
00:07:03,440 --> 00:07:05,600
That's fine,
that's a perfectly normal reaction.

136
00:07:11,480 --> 00:07:13,440
Basically, you've to get
that guy on the block

137
00:07:13,520 --> 00:07:15,680
and stop the other one
from shooting him. It's so sick.

138
00:07:15,760 --> 00:07:18,320
I, I got that guy.
That was, like, six months ago.

139
00:07:18,400 --> 00:07:20,080
What you actually have to do
is flick it that way.

140
00:07:20,160 --> 00:07:21,280
No, but I'm saying...

141
00:07:21,360 --> 00:07:22,920
You Coal Hill kids?

142
00:07:23,880 --> 00:07:26,680
-Yeah, so what if we are?
-Then get to Coal Hill.

143
00:07:27,520 --> 00:07:29,280
We've got a free period, mate.

144
00:07:29,440 --> 00:07:31,040
You want me to take your names?

145
00:07:31,840 --> 00:07:32,880
Come on.

146
00:07:34,920 --> 00:07:36,160
This is unfair, mate.

147
00:07:38,440 --> 00:07:39,440
(THUDDING)

148
00:07:40,040 --> 00:07:41,960
Always come in threes.

149
00:07:44,080 --> 00:07:46,040
Oi! I know you're in there.

150
00:07:57,360 --> 00:08:00,640
Hello? I'm a police officer.

151
00:08:06,520 --> 00:08:08,480
There's no point hiding.

152
00:08:11,280 --> 00:08:12,480
Do you hear me?

153
00:08:13,800 --> 00:08:15,400
Come on, kiddo.

154
00:08:15,560 --> 00:08:19,800
ROBOTIC VOICE: Five. Stop intruder.
Five. Stop intruder.

155
00:08:20,200 --> 00:08:22,720
Turn your game off,
it's time for school.

156
00:08:22,800 --> 00:08:25,760
Come on! Stop messing about!

157
00:08:27,320 --> 00:08:30,640
ROBOTIC VOICE:
Problem. Solution: destroy.

158
00:08:31,160 --> 00:08:32,160
(SCREAMING)

159
00:08:40,960 --> 00:08:45,120
"...though unheard by Lydia,
was caught by Elizabeth

160
00:08:45,200 --> 00:08:48,160
"and as it assured her
that Darcy was not less..."

161
00:08:51,080 --> 00:08:54,480
-You all right, Miss Oswald?
-Yes, Kelvin, I'm fine, you carry on.

162
00:08:55,720 --> 00:08:57,800
KELVIN: Um, "every feeling
of displeasure

163
00:08:57,880 --> 00:08:59,960
"against the former
was so sharpened...”

164
00:09:00,040 --> 00:09:02,400
Can I help you, Mr Smith?

165
00:09:02,920 --> 00:09:05,280
-Wrong.
-I'm sorry?

166
00:09:05,560 --> 00:09:09,480
On the board. Wrong. Wrong.

167
00:09:09,560 --> 00:09:12,400
Oh, no, no, no. No. You don't do this.

168
00:09:12,480 --> 00:09:14,880
You are the caretaker,
this is not what you do.

169
00:09:14,960 --> 00:09:16,600
-Just taking care.
-Not your area!

170
00:09:16,680 --> 00:09:20,120
Jane Austen wrote
Pride and Prejudice in 1796.

171
00:09:20,200 --> 00:09:24,040
(CLEARING THROAT) This is Mr Smith,
the temporary caretaker,

172
00:09:24,120 --> 00:09:25,120
and he's a bit confused.

173
00:09:25,200 --> 00:09:29,400
Not in 1797, because she didn't
have the time. She was so busy...

174
00:09:29,480 --> 00:09:31,880
Oh, what, and I suppose she was
your bezzie mate, was she?

175
00:09:31,960 --> 00:09:33,120
And you went on holidays together

176
00:09:33,200 --> 00:09:35,480
and then you got kidnapped
by Boggans from space

177
00:09:35,560 --> 00:09:38,440
and then you all formed
a band and met Buddy Holly.

178
00:09:39,560 --> 00:09:42,160
No, I read the book.
There's a bio at the back.

179
00:09:42,280 --> 00:09:44,040
Get down.

180
00:09:45,160 --> 00:09:46,600
-Boggans?
-Go!

181
00:09:49,360 --> 00:09:50,360
(SCHOOL BELL RINGING)

182
00:09:51,240 --> 00:09:54,400
Right, that's it.
Uh, well done, Kelvin. Get going.

183
00:09:54,480 --> 00:09:56,600
See you all in a couple of days.
Thanks very much.

184
00:09:56,680 --> 00:09:59,000
Miss, what about our homework?

185
00:09:59,120 --> 00:10:01,440
Who asks for homework? Amateur.

186
00:10:09,040 --> 00:10:11,160
-Miss Oswald...
-Oh, hello, Tobias, can't really stop.

187
00:10:11,240 --> 00:10:14,120
I'm on the school football team
against Durants on Thursday.

188
00:10:14,200 --> 00:10:17,240
Sorry, but can I go early
from English Thursday afternoon?

189
00:10:17,320 --> 00:10:19,000
Tobias, you can do whatever you want.

190
00:10:19,080 --> 00:10:21,920
-Ah, Clara, can I have a quick word?
-Actually, I, erm...

191
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:25,240
Two weeks Saturday, the fete,
can I put you down for the tombola

192
00:10:25,320 --> 00:10:27,480
and the raffle?
James H can't cover it now.

193
00:10:27,560 --> 00:10:30,280
His wife's going into hospital.
Hip replacement. Constant agony.

194
00:10:30,360 --> 00:10:31,400
Great!

195
00:10:31,800 --> 00:10:35,000
No, awful. That's terrible. Awful.
I hope she'll be okay.

196
00:10:35,080 --> 00:10:37,520
Um, I'll do anything.
Anything. Okay. Bye.

197
00:10:41,640 --> 00:10:44,520
Miss Oswald, Katie Sharp says
I pulled her hair in Biology.

198
00:10:44,600 --> 00:10:46,280
Courtney, you are big enough
to look after yourself.

199
00:10:46,360 --> 00:10:48,560
Next class, jog on,
I need to talk to Mr Pink.

200
00:10:48,640 --> 00:10:49,840
Ozzie loves the Squaddie.

201
00:10:49,920 --> 00:10:51,440
-What was that?
-Nothing.

202
00:10:51,520 --> 00:10:53,400
ADRIAN: Of course, Danny Pink
is your man, Mr Smith.

203
00:10:53,480 --> 00:10:56,280
Five years' military experience,
sergeant, here and Afghan,

204
00:10:56,360 --> 00:10:59,640
so electrics, boilers, if you need
a hand, give him a shout.

205
00:10:59,720 --> 00:11:02,120
I, I've helped Atif
with a couple of things.

206
00:11:02,200 --> 00:11:04,920
I'm sure I won't needing you, Sergeant.
Fully qualified.

207
00:11:05,240 --> 00:11:06,240
(ELECTRICITY CRACKLING)

208
00:11:07,560 --> 00:11:10,720
-You best get back to your PE class.
-Uh, I teach maths.

209
00:11:10,800 --> 00:11:13,440
-Do you? What, in emergencies?
-No, I'm a maths teacher.

210
00:11:13,520 --> 00:11:14,960
Yeah, he's a maths teacher...

211
00:11:15,040 --> 00:11:16,640
Mohammed, put that down!

212
00:11:16,760 --> 00:11:18,840
How does that work?
What if the kids have questions?

213
00:11:18,920 --> 00:11:20,200
-About what?
-Maths.

214
00:11:20,280 --> 00:11:21,960
I answer them. I'm a maths teacher.

215
00:11:22,040 --> 00:11:23,520
But he said you were a soldier.

216
00:11:23,920 --> 00:11:26,000
Yeah. I was a soldier.
Now I'm a maths teacher.

217
00:11:26,080 --> 00:11:27,720
But what about all the PE?

218
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:30,040
I don't teach PE. I'm not a PE teacher.

219
00:11:30,840 --> 00:11:32,640
Sorry, that seems very unlikely.

220
00:11:32,720 --> 00:11:35,640
Er... (CLEARING THROAT)
Excuse me, Mr Pink,

221
00:11:35,720 --> 00:11:37,400
I think Maths 9-M4 are waiting.

222
00:11:37,480 --> 00:11:39,200
Yes, you'd better run along, Sergeant.

223
00:11:39,280 --> 00:11:41,200
That ball isn't going to
kick itself, is it?

224
00:11:41,280 --> 00:11:43,560
I'm not a PE teacher,
I'm a maths teacher.

225
00:11:45,120 --> 00:11:47,960
Nope, sorry.
No, I can't retain that.

226
00:11:48,040 --> 00:11:49,960
I've tried, it's just not going in.

227
00:11:57,520 --> 00:12:00,440
So... Pink.
The name remind you of anything?

228
00:12:00,520 --> 00:12:02,440
Yeah. The colour.

229
00:12:03,520 --> 00:12:04,760
Colonel Orson Pink?

230
00:12:04,840 --> 00:12:06,840
The guy we met
at the end of the universe.

231
00:12:07,080 --> 00:12:10,440
Oh, yeah. Okay, yeah, same name,
doesn't look anything like him, though.

232
00:12:10,720 --> 00:12:12,080
Looks very like him.

233
00:12:12,200 --> 00:12:14,720
DOCTOR: Does he? I don't know.
Who remembers a PE teacher?

234
00:12:14,800 --> 00:12:15,800
Oh, never mind.

235
00:12:17,200 --> 00:12:19,200
What are you doing? What's in there?

236
00:12:19,440 --> 00:12:22,000
So... Is he here, then?

237
00:12:22,080 --> 00:12:23,080
Is who here?

238
00:12:23,640 --> 00:12:25,960
The one you keep going on
serious dates with.

239
00:12:26,040 --> 00:12:28,920
If he is, are you going to start
talking like a normal human being?

240
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:31,440
-I promise I won't. I'm being nice.
-Doctor...

241
00:12:31,520 --> 00:12:34,280
-Clara. Got this period free, yes?
-No. Yes.

242
00:12:34,360 --> 00:12:36,960
-Great. Shakespeare.
-Sorry, what, Adrian?

243
00:12:38,440 --> 00:12:40,800
Oh... I see.

244
00:12:42,800 --> 00:12:45,760
-You see what?
-Nothing. Nothing at all.

245
00:12:46,200 --> 00:12:48,440
Excuse me. We have to
talk about 7he Tempest,

246
00:12:48,520 --> 00:12:51,560
in light of the changes to the Sixth
Form Shakespeare module blah-di-blah.

247
00:12:51,640 --> 00:12:53,600
Yes. Sorry, of course.

248
00:12:54,920 --> 00:12:57,680
Yes, yes, no, of course,
of course, yes.

249
00:12:57,760 --> 00:13:02,080
Don't mind this old man.
You two kids just pop off together.

250
00:13:02,280 --> 00:13:04,120
Why are you talking like an idiot?

251
00:13:04,200 --> 00:13:06,800
I'm a caretaker, don't mind me.

252
00:13:06,960 --> 00:13:07,960
(BOTH CHUCKLING WEAKLY)

253
00:13:08,320 --> 00:13:10,280
What we have to get across, I feel,

254
00:13:10,360 --> 00:13:15,320
is that fascinating enigma
of its...not-finishedness.

255
00:13:15,400 --> 00:13:17,040
Mmm, yes, good point, Ade.

256
00:13:20,240 --> 00:13:21,920
Oh, Clara.

257
00:13:35,240 --> 00:13:40,040
What does that mean? Kids.
What's the matter with kids today?

258
00:13:48,080 --> 00:13:49,080
(BEEPING)

259
00:13:50,720 --> 00:13:52,160
CLARA: Hey, I said you could play chess,

260
00:13:52,240 --> 00:13:54,600
I did not say you could play
football on the chessboard.

261
00:13:54,680 --> 00:13:57,240
Jack, Morgan, come on,
help me out, clear it up.

262
00:13:57,640 --> 00:14:00,320
(WHISTLING ANOTHER BRICK IN THE WALL)

263
00:14:08,200 --> 00:14:10,080
And one for luck.

264
00:14:10,160 --> 00:14:11,160
(BEEPING)

265
00:14:13,720 --> 00:14:15,960
Okay. Now we're in business.

266
00:14:16,160 --> 00:14:20,000
Let's see the lie of the land.
Time to see what's going on.

267
00:14:24,280 --> 00:14:25,320
Hello?

268
00:14:26,560 --> 00:14:27,720
Oi.

269
00:14:29,120 --> 00:14:31,480
What are you doing? Are you in there?

270
00:14:31,680 --> 00:14:33,440
DOCTOR: Mirror, mirror on the wall,

271
00:14:33,520 --> 00:14:36,360
who's the most dangerous of them all?

272
00:14:36,560 --> 00:14:40,120
There's been a spillage in
Geography, I need some paper towels.

273
00:14:40,960 --> 00:14:43,320
-Can't you read?
-Course I can read. Read what?

274
00:14:43,400 --> 00:14:45,920
The door. It says, "Keep Out."”

275
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:47,960
No, it says, "Go Away Humans."

276
00:14:48,840 --> 00:14:50,000
Oh, so it does.

277
00:14:50,080 --> 00:14:52,120
Never lose your temper
in the middle of a door sign.

278
00:14:52,200 --> 00:14:54,840
What was you doing in there?
What's that box?

279
00:14:54,920 --> 00:14:58,800
A caretaker's box.
Every caretaker has their own box.

280
00:14:58,960 --> 00:15:00,240
It says, "Police."

281
00:15:00,320 --> 00:15:03,160
Exactly. There's a policeman
in there, in case of emergencies

282
00:15:03,240 --> 00:15:04,240
and children.

283
00:15:04,320 --> 00:15:06,800
-Towels, there, g-g-go.
-What was that green glow?

284
00:15:06,880 --> 00:15:08,720
There was a green glow
coming from in there.

285
00:15:08,840 --> 00:15:11,120
-What was it?
-Of course there was.

286
00:15:11,200 --> 00:15:13,360
-What's a policeman without a death ray?
-(SCHOOL BELL RINGING)

287
00:15:13,800 --> 00:15:15,560
Oh, listen, there's the bell,
off you go.

288
00:15:15,640 --> 00:15:17,040
Haven't you got
shoplifting to go to?

289
00:15:17,120 --> 00:15:18,520
I'm going to tell
the Headmaster.

290
00:15:18,600 --> 00:15:20,640
Oh, yes, fine. Well, cut along,
you're running out of time.

291
00:15:20,720 --> 00:15:22,440
-For what?
-Everything.

292
00:15:22,680 --> 00:15:24,920
Human beings have incredibly
short lifespans.

293
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:27,680
Frankly, you should all be
in a permanent state of panic.

294
00:15:27,760 --> 00:15:30,760
-Tick tock, tick tock.
-You're weird.

295
00:15:30,840 --> 00:15:32,600
Yes, I am. What about you?

296
00:15:32,680 --> 00:15:34,720
I'm a disruptive influence.

297
00:15:35,800 --> 00:15:38,200
-Good to meet you.
-And you!

298
00:15:38,280 --> 00:15:40,320
-Now, get lost.
-Okay.

299
00:15:42,400 --> 00:15:45,000
Hello, miss, love to the Squaddie.

300
00:15:45,120 --> 00:15:46,640
Sorry, what did you say?

301
00:15:48,520 --> 00:15:49,720
What was she doing here?

302
00:15:49,800 --> 00:15:53,480
Paper towels.
Now, I imagine you have many questions.

303
00:15:53,560 --> 00:15:55,600
Fire away, I won't answer any of them.

304
00:15:55,680 --> 00:15:57,480
-What were they like?
-What were who like?

305
00:15:57,560 --> 00:15:58,560
The others before me.

306
00:15:58,640 --> 00:16:00,560
Did they let you get away
with this kind of thing?

307
00:16:01,200 --> 00:16:04,040
-This school is in danger.
-Well, it's lucky I'm here, then.

308
00:16:04,120 --> 00:16:06,000
-From you.
-Me?

309
00:16:06,080 --> 00:16:08,160
You wouldn't be here
if there wasn't an alien threat nearby.

310
00:16:08,240 --> 00:16:10,520
Your strategy for dealing with it
involves endangering this school.

311
00:16:10,600 --> 00:16:11,600
You don't know that.

312
00:16:11,680 --> 00:16:13,360
I don't know anything because
you haven't told me anything,

313
00:16:13,440 --> 00:16:14,560
which means I wouldn't approve,
which means

314
00:16:14,640 --> 00:16:16,120
you are endangering the school.

315
00:16:17,760 --> 00:16:19,120
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

316
00:16:21,720 --> 00:16:22,880
What's that?

317
00:16:22,960 --> 00:16:25,680
It's a scanner. I'm scanning.
Why do I keep you around?

318
00:16:25,760 --> 00:16:28,040
Because the alternative would be
developing a conscience of your own.

319
00:16:28,120 --> 00:16:29,120
Scanning for what?

320
00:16:29,680 --> 00:16:32,160
DOCTOR: Any alien technology
in this vicinity should show up.

321
00:16:32,280 --> 00:16:34,960
I used to have a teacher
exactly like you.

322
00:16:35,040 --> 00:16:36,760
You still do. Pay attention.

323
00:16:38,800 --> 00:16:40,160
What the hell is it?

324
00:16:40,840 --> 00:16:42,760
DOCTOR: A Skovox Blitzer,

325
00:16:43,160 --> 00:16:46,240
one of the deadliest
killing machines ever created.

326
00:16:46,320 --> 00:16:48,480
Probably homed in here
because of artron emissions.

327
00:16:48,560 --> 00:16:50,840
You've had enough of them
in this area over the years.

328
00:16:50,920 --> 00:16:54,880
There's enough explosive in its armoury
to take out the whole planet.

329
00:16:55,720 --> 00:16:57,600
Then leave it alone.

330
00:16:57,720 --> 00:17:00,840
Sooner or later,
it will creep from its hidey-hole

331
00:17:00,960 --> 00:17:03,840
and some military idiot
will try to attack it.

332
00:17:05,400 --> 00:17:07,440
The world is full of PE teachers.

333
00:17:10,360 --> 00:17:14,840
So, your insanely dangerous plan is?

334
00:17:16,200 --> 00:17:18,200
A new watch. Tiny bit disappointed.

335
00:17:18,280 --> 00:17:20,080
This is a very special watch.

336
00:17:20,160 --> 00:17:21,160
Mmm.

337
00:17:24,240 --> 00:17:25,240
(BEEPING)

338
00:17:26,920 --> 00:17:27,960
Doctor?

339
00:17:29,560 --> 00:17:30,680
Oi! Ow!

340
00:17:31,800 --> 00:17:33,880
Did you just flick my nose?

341
00:17:35,920 --> 00:17:37,840
You're invisible. (LAUGHING)

342
00:17:37,920 --> 00:17:39,280
Oh, my God, that's incredible!

343
00:17:39,360 --> 00:17:42,040
DOCTOR: Correct. I am invisible
and I am incredible.

344
00:17:42,120 --> 00:17:44,560
It's simply a matter of reversing
light waves. Hang on, I'm coming back.

345
00:17:44,640 --> 00:17:45,640
All right, where are you?

346
00:17:45,720 --> 00:17:47,120
Ooh! (GIGGLING)

347
00:17:47,200 --> 00:17:50,600
So, I give the Blitzer a tiny whiff
of non-threatening alien tech,

348
00:17:50,680 --> 00:17:53,480
I lead it back here, but I don't
want it to scan me, hence invisible.

349
00:17:53,560 --> 00:17:57,120
So, you're, you're leading the thing
here? To a school? My, my school?

350
00:17:57,200 --> 00:17:59,160
"My school"? Oh, that is telling.

351
00:17:59,240 --> 00:18:01,240
This is the only
suitably empty place in the area.

352
00:18:01,320 --> 00:18:04,480
I've set up a circle of time mines
around the school.

353
00:18:04,560 --> 00:18:06,960
-Chronodyne generators.
-Ooh.

354
00:18:07,040 --> 00:18:08,040
Bit unstable.

355
00:18:08,120 --> 00:18:11,720
I switch them on, the Blitzer gets
sucked into a big old time vortex,

356
00:18:11,800 --> 00:18:14,440
billions of years into the future.
It's dead easy. Tiny bit boring.

357
00:18:14,520 --> 00:18:16,880
-I'll need a book and a sandwich.
-And me. You're not doing this alone.

358
00:18:16,960 --> 00:18:20,560
I don't need you this time.
I'll see you tomorrow.

359
00:18:20,640 --> 00:18:24,960
We'll go somewhere nice.
Ancient Egypt. Crocodilopolis.

360
00:18:25,040 --> 00:18:28,160
They worship a big crocodile there,
so the name is a useful coincidence.

361
00:18:28,520 --> 00:18:30,360
Go and canoodle with your boyfriend.

362
00:18:35,240 --> 00:18:39,240
Come on. I wasn't born yesterday,
far from it.

363
00:18:39,360 --> 00:18:40,520
You did recognise him.

364
00:18:40,600 --> 00:18:44,240
Possibly reminded me of a certain
dashing young time traveller.

365
00:18:44,320 --> 00:18:46,920
Oh, of course you recognised him.

366
00:18:47,080 --> 00:18:51,560
Sorry. Stupid. I...
I underestimated you.

367
00:18:51,640 --> 00:18:53,320
It's easily done,
there's a lot to estimate.

368
00:18:53,400 --> 00:18:55,160
And you, you like him?

369
00:18:55,480 --> 00:18:59,280
Yes, I like him. Very, very much.

370
00:18:59,840 --> 00:19:02,280
Go home and canoodle.
Doctor's orders. Come on.

371
00:19:02,440 --> 00:19:03,440
(EXHALING)

372
00:19:03,560 --> 00:19:05,920
Just this once, I'm doing what I'm told.

373
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:07,640
-(CHUCKLING)
-Oh, sing hosanna.

374
00:19:08,120 --> 00:19:10,160
CLARA: (EXHALING) So easy.

375
00:19:20,760 --> 00:19:22,040
Miss Oswald.

376
00:19:22,120 --> 00:19:25,080
-Ah, Mr... Mr Pink.
-Are you still on for tonight?

377
00:19:25,160 --> 00:19:28,240
'Cause you had your
"I'm about to cancel" frown on.

378
00:19:28,680 --> 00:19:29,920
There's a specific frown?

379
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:33,320
And I was going to say, it's okay,
I might have a thing, so...

380
00:19:33,440 --> 00:19:34,440
A, a thing?

381
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:37,000
Uh...

382
00:19:37,280 --> 00:19:40,600
-Tomorrow instead?
-Uh, tomorrow's parents' evening.

383
00:19:41,200 --> 00:19:42,720
Not all evening.

384
00:19:43,200 --> 00:19:45,040
No. Not all evening.

385
00:19:47,120 --> 00:19:48,760
What do you think of him?

386
00:19:48,920 --> 00:19:51,480
Uh, who? The, the caretaker?

387
00:19:51,560 --> 00:19:53,440
Where did he come from?
What was he before?

388
00:19:54,480 --> 00:19:56,360
He doesn't seem like a caretaker.

389
00:19:56,560 --> 00:19:58,600
Well, he speaks very highly of you.

390
00:20:03,520 --> 00:20:06,640
Anyway, um, goodnight, Miss Oswald.

391
00:20:08,440 --> 00:20:10,680
Goodnight, Mr Pink.

392
00:20:18,080 --> 00:20:19,440
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

393
00:20:19,960 --> 00:20:20,320
And we're off.

394
00:20:20,320 --> 00:20:21,040
And we're off.

395
00:20:24,440 --> 00:20:25,960
(BEEPING)

396
00:20:37,480 --> 00:20:38,480
(BEEPING)

397
00:20:50,360 --> 00:20:51,760
Home sweet home.

398
00:20:53,600 --> 00:20:54,600
(BEEPING)

399
00:20:55,280 --> 00:20:57,440
Canoodling cancelled,
if you need a hand...

400
00:21:00,560 --> 00:21:02,040
Doctor?

401
00:21:02,840 --> 00:21:04,240
You invisible?

402
00:21:05,640 --> 00:21:08,360
(SIGHING)
I am so going to confiscate that watch.

403
00:21:09,200 --> 00:21:12,000
DOCTOR: Where are you,
my sleeping beauty?

404
00:21:15,480 --> 00:21:16,480
(BLITZER POWERING UP)

405
00:21:20,280 --> 00:21:22,160
DOCTOR: Gotcha! Let's dance!

406
00:21:24,080 --> 00:21:25,520
Doctor?

407
00:21:26,840 --> 00:21:28,040
Where are you?

408
00:21:29,720 --> 00:21:30,720
(KNOCKING)

409
00:21:30,960 --> 00:21:31,960
Hello?

410
00:21:33,800 --> 00:21:34,800
(BEEPING)

411
00:21:39,400 --> 00:21:41,800
BLITZER: Nine. Stop query. Rescan.

412
00:21:41,880 --> 00:21:45,200
Target reacquired. Success. Success.

413
00:21:45,840 --> 00:21:47,560
DOCTOR: Come on,
come on, come on.

414
00:21:47,920 --> 00:21:49,400
-(FOOTSTEPS)
-Gangway!

415
00:21:52,600 --> 00:21:54,720
Not far now. Come on.

416
00:21:55,680 --> 00:21:58,400
BLITZER: Nine.
Stop parsing data. Pursue.

417
00:21:58,480 --> 00:21:59,480
DOCTOR: Bingo.

418
00:22:02,560 --> 00:22:04,200
BUTZER: Target reacquired.

419
00:22:06,240 --> 00:22:07,280
Hello?

420
00:22:11,600 --> 00:22:12,600
(RHYTHMIC BEEPING)

421
00:22:13,320 --> 00:22:18,120
What? Red, red, red. No. No, no, no!

422
00:22:18,360 --> 00:22:22,560
BLITZER: Range, 71.489.
Scan complete. Problem. Problem.

423
00:22:22,680 --> 00:22:27,320
Listen. I'm unarmed.
I'm peaceful. Do you understand?

424
00:22:27,960 --> 00:22:30,240
I know that you shouldn't be
on this planet

425
00:22:30,320 --> 00:22:31,560
but I can help you with that. I...

426
00:22:31,640 --> 00:22:33,840
BLITZER: Problem. Solution: destroy.

427
00:22:33,920 --> 00:22:35,000
I want a word with you.

428
00:22:35,200 --> 00:22:37,520
DOCTOR: Get back!
BLITZER: Problem. Solution: destroy.

429
00:22:41,080 --> 00:22:42,800
Go. Get away from me!

430
00:22:42,880 --> 00:22:43,880
(GRUNTING)

431
00:22:47,520 --> 00:22:49,320
BUTZER: Temporal disrupt.

432
00:22:50,560 --> 00:22:53,440
Warning. Warning. Temporal failure.

433
00:22:53,760 --> 00:22:56,360
No, no, no, no. Doctor, stop!

434
00:22:57,560 --> 00:22:58,840
Doctor!

435
00:22:58,920 --> 00:23:02,080
BLITZER: Warning, system failure.
Abort. Abort.

436
00:23:02,200 --> 00:23:03,200
(GRUNTING)

437
00:23:12,560 --> 00:23:17,600
Oh! Oh, well done, PE.
Brilliant work!

438
00:23:19,040 --> 00:23:21,840
"What's this? A chronodyne generator?

439
00:23:21,920 --> 00:23:23,880
"I'll just deactivate that, shall I?

440
00:23:23,960 --> 00:23:26,680
"I've got a swimming certificate,
so that qualifies me

441
00:23:26,760 --> 00:23:28,160
"to meddle with higher technology.

442
00:23:28,240 --> 00:23:31,400
"Never mind that some people are
actually trying to save the planet.

443
00:23:31,520 --> 00:23:35,640
"Oh, no. There's only room in my head
for cross-country and the offside rule."”

444
00:23:36,280 --> 00:23:38,840
-Danny, what are you doing here?
-I was checking up on him.

445
00:23:38,960 --> 00:23:41,800
He's been up to something, fiddling
with the electric, but what the...

446
00:23:44,120 --> 00:23:45,200
No.

447
00:23:45,760 --> 00:23:46,760
What...

448
00:23:47,840 --> 00:23:49,920
Did you see that thing?
Tell me you saw that thing.

449
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:52,720
I saw the thing, yeah.
Doctor, are we safe, is the planet safe?

450
00:23:52,800 --> 00:23:53,800
It's gone?

451
00:23:53,920 --> 00:23:56,520
Yes, yes, yes, yes, for the moment.
But the thing is, you see,

452
00:23:56,600 --> 00:23:59,360
the chronodyne generators
have to be precisely aligned

453
00:23:59,440 --> 00:24:00,720
to generate the vortex,

454
00:24:00,800 --> 00:24:02,640
but the sergeant here,
he went and moved one.

455
00:24:02,720 --> 00:24:04,840
Okay, but the chronodyne worked,
it's gone.

456
00:24:04,920 --> 00:24:06,120
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

457
00:24:07,200 --> 00:24:08,440
But not far enough.

458
00:24:09,040 --> 00:24:12,880
The vortex will open here again,
but not in a billion years.

459
00:24:12,960 --> 00:24:14,120
Then when?

460
00:24:14,200 --> 00:24:16,600
Er, 74 hours. Three days.

461
00:24:16,680 --> 00:24:21,520
Three days to think of something new
because now it knows what to expect.

462
00:24:21,600 --> 00:24:26,200
Now it has scanned me
and it will kill me on sight,

463
00:24:26,280 --> 00:24:27,880
thanks to PE here.

464
00:24:29,840 --> 00:24:31,720
Clara, why are you talking
to him like that?

465
00:24:34,160 --> 00:24:37,480
Why are you using words
like "chronodyne"?

466
00:24:38,160 --> 00:24:40,040
Was that thing a space thing?

467
00:24:44,400 --> 00:24:46,600
Oh, my God, you're from space.

468
00:24:50,680 --> 00:24:53,200
You're a spacewoman.
You said you were from Blackpool.

469
00:24:55,960 --> 00:24:59,240
It's a play! For the summer fete.

470
00:24:59,320 --> 00:25:01,000
-It's a what?
-Yes, it's a play.

471
00:25:01,080 --> 00:25:02,840
Shut up, it is a play.

472
00:25:02,920 --> 00:25:06,800
We are rehearsing a play.
(SHUSHING) A surprise play!

473
00:25:06,880 --> 00:25:10,400
And, erm, you see, the vortex thing
is, is a lighting effect.

474
00:25:10,480 --> 00:25:11,480
Very clever.

475
00:25:11,560 --> 00:25:16,040
And that thing is one of the kids.
In fancy dress.

476
00:25:16,120 --> 00:25:17,760
(LAUGHING) Really.

477
00:25:18,360 --> 00:25:20,880
Really, really good fancy dress.

478
00:25:20,960 --> 00:25:22,240
How stupid do you think I am?

479
00:25:22,320 --> 00:25:23,920
I'm willing to put a number on it.

480
00:25:24,320 --> 00:25:26,240
I'm not a moron, Clara.

481
00:25:27,080 --> 00:25:29,040
And he's not the caretaker.

482
00:25:30,840 --> 00:25:33,840
He's...your dad.

483
00:25:34,280 --> 00:25:36,040
Your space dad.

484
00:25:36,600 --> 00:25:39,680
Oh, genius.

485
00:25:39,880 --> 00:25:43,680
That is... That is really,
really brilliant reasoning.

486
00:25:43,800 --> 00:25:45,160
How can you think that I'm her dad

487
00:25:45,240 --> 00:25:46,960
when we both look exactly the same age?

488
00:25:47,040 --> 00:25:48,840
-We do not look the same age.
-I was being kind.

489
00:25:48,920 --> 00:25:50,160
Right, I'm going to hypnotise him,

490
00:25:50,240 --> 00:25:51,440
-I'm going to erase his memory.
-Doctor, stop!

491
00:25:51,520 --> 00:25:52,800
Tiny little brain,
will only take a moment.

492
00:25:52,880 --> 00:25:53,880
He's my boyfriend.

493
00:25:53,960 --> 00:25:56,640
Well, I'll try not to erase the
whole thing. I'll leave the bits that...

494
00:25:56,720 --> 00:25:59,880
He's my boyfriend.
I thought you'd figured this out.

495
00:26:00,720 --> 00:26:01,840
-Him?
-Yes, him.

496
00:26:01,920 --> 00:26:03,640
-No, he's not.
-Yes, he is.

497
00:26:04,240 --> 00:26:06,160
-Yes, I am.
-But he's a PE teacher.

498
00:26:06,240 --> 00:26:07,880
You wouldn't go out with a PE teacher.

499
00:26:08,440 --> 00:26:10,480
It's a mistake.
You've made a boyfriend error.

500
00:26:10,560 --> 00:26:13,120
I am not a PE teacher.
I am a maths teacher!

501
00:26:13,200 --> 00:26:15,080
You're a soldier.
Why would you go out with a soldier?

502
00:26:15,160 --> 00:26:18,160
-Why not get a dog or a big plant?
-Because I love him!

503
00:26:26,440 --> 00:26:29,400
Why would you say that?
Is this part of the surprise play?

504
00:26:29,600 --> 00:26:31,800
(SIGHING) There is no surprise play.

505
00:26:32,160 --> 00:26:35,080
Oh, it's a roller coaster
with you tonight, isn't it?

506
00:26:35,160 --> 00:26:37,040
What about the handsome one,
the one with the bow tie?

507
00:26:37,120 --> 00:26:39,680
Who? Adrian? No, no, no.
He's just a friend and not my type.

508
00:26:39,760 --> 00:26:41,960
Clara, are you going to
explain any of this?

509
00:26:42,520 --> 00:26:43,880
Who is this guy?

510
00:26:45,480 --> 00:26:46,520
(CHUCKLING)

511
00:26:46,600 --> 00:26:48,560
The Doctor is...

512
00:26:51,080 --> 00:26:53,640
-Go on.
-Yes, explain.

513
00:26:54,200 --> 00:26:56,080
Who is he?
Why have you never mentioned him?

514
00:26:56,160 --> 00:26:59,640
Because...he's an alien.

515
00:27:02,800 --> 00:27:05,600
-DANNY: Are you an alien?
-No, no, no. I'm still from Blackpool.

516
00:27:07,400 --> 00:27:10,440
Me and the Doctor,
we travel through time and space.

517
00:27:10,520 --> 00:27:12,520
DOCTOR: Exhibit A.

518
00:27:13,680 --> 00:27:15,240
It's called a Tardis

519
00:27:15,640 --> 00:27:18,600
but it's disguised
as an old police phone box.

520
00:27:19,160 --> 00:27:20,320
-Huh?
-It's bigger on the inside.

521
00:27:20,400 --> 00:27:22,880
And it's bigger on the inside
than the outside.

522
00:27:25,120 --> 00:27:26,320
Voila.

523
00:27:28,320 --> 00:27:30,560
CLARA: And we travel the universe in it.

524
00:27:46,720 --> 00:27:48,400
And what about that thing?
Did you bring it here?

525
00:27:48,480 --> 00:27:51,680
No, I'm going to protect you
from that thing.

526
00:27:52,000 --> 00:27:53,440
You said it was coming back.

527
00:27:53,520 --> 00:27:55,720
Yes, it is coming back. Thanks to you.

528
00:27:55,800 --> 00:27:59,480
This is a school.
We have to evacuate, call the Army.

529
00:27:59,560 --> 00:28:02,280
And that is the most dangerous
thing right there.

530
00:28:03,200 --> 00:28:04,680
Are you sure hypnotising
is not on the menu?

531
00:28:04,760 --> 00:28:05,760
Yes.

532
00:28:06,520 --> 00:28:08,760
Well, we need to get help.
This is an emergency.

533
00:28:08,840 --> 00:28:11,280
Look, take him away, shut him up,
shut him down,

534
00:28:11,360 --> 00:28:13,120
up or down, doesn't matter to me.

535
00:28:13,200 --> 00:28:16,240
-I've got a lot of work to do. Again.
-Will you be okay?

536
00:28:16,400 --> 00:28:20,480
Why wouldn't I be okay?
I was fine till you two blundered in.

537
00:28:20,560 --> 00:28:22,000
Am I just being ignored?

538
00:28:22,080 --> 00:28:24,080
Oh, come on, Danny.
It's all right, it's...

539
00:28:24,160 --> 00:28:25,680
Come on, it's all fine.

540
00:28:25,760 --> 00:28:29,280
You'll be okay.
Let's, uh, get those legs moving...

541
00:28:29,360 --> 00:28:31,760
That's it, down those stairs.
Yep, that's it.

542
00:28:31,880 --> 00:28:35,600
This can all be explained
and everything will be fine.

543
00:28:35,680 --> 00:28:39,320
And when this is all over,
you can finish the job.

544
00:28:39,800 --> 00:28:40,840
How do you mean?

545
00:28:40,960 --> 00:28:44,720
Well, you've explained me to him.
You haven't explained him to me.

546
00:28:57,160 --> 00:28:59,160
CLARA: What do you think?

547
00:29:04,520 --> 00:29:05,560
Say something.

548
00:29:09,120 --> 00:29:10,320
So...

549
00:29:12,120 --> 00:29:15,760
there's an alien
that used to look like Adrian.

550
00:29:17,920 --> 00:29:20,600
Hmm... Then he turned
into a Scottish caretaker

551
00:29:20,680 --> 00:29:23,680
and every now and then, when I'm
not looking, you elope with him.

552
00:29:23,760 --> 00:29:25,120
I don't elope.

553
00:29:25,200 --> 00:29:26,600
-Do you love him?
-No.

554
00:29:27,840 --> 00:29:29,600
Really had enough of the lies.

555
00:29:31,800 --> 00:29:34,440
-Not in that way.
-What other way is there?

556
00:29:34,520 --> 00:29:36,480
-You know what I mean.
-I don't know what you mean.

557
00:29:36,560 --> 00:29:39,280
I know what you tell me,
which isn't always the truth.

558
00:29:42,120 --> 00:29:44,120
-Danny...
-Why do you do it?

559
00:29:46,560 --> 00:29:48,640
Why do you fly off in the box with him?

560
00:29:49,880 --> 00:29:52,800
The truth, please, just this once.

561
00:29:57,680 --> 00:29:58,840
Because...

562
00:30:00,640 --> 00:30:01,920
it's amazing.

563
00:30:03,920 --> 00:30:06,920
Because...I see wonders.

564
00:30:09,400 --> 00:30:10,440
Okay.

565
00:30:19,160 --> 00:30:20,240
What are you thinking?

566
00:30:20,640 --> 00:30:21,640
(LAUGHING)

567
00:30:21,880 --> 00:30:23,160
There's a good question.

568
00:30:27,320 --> 00:30:29,640
It's funny, you only really know
what someone thinks of you

569
00:30:29,720 --> 00:30:31,720
when you know what lies
they've told you.

570
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:37,560
You say you've seen wonders,
you've seen amazing things

571
00:30:37,640 --> 00:30:40,640
and you kept them secret.

572
00:30:41,960 --> 00:30:43,000
From me.

573
00:30:46,200 --> 00:30:48,240
So what do you think of me, Clara?

574
00:30:50,160 --> 00:30:53,560
-Please, tell me how I fix this.
-I just want to know who you are.

575
00:30:53,640 --> 00:30:54,960
You know who I am.

576
00:30:56,240 --> 00:31:01,080
When you're with him.
When you're with the Doctor.

577
00:31:07,160 --> 00:31:08,920
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

578
00:31:11,800 --> 00:31:15,040
Okay, I think we've just about got
enough time before parents' evening.

579
00:31:15,240 --> 00:31:18,000
An invisibility watch?
Not even a ring.

580
00:31:18,360 --> 00:31:19,800
Press the button on the side,
you're invisible.

581
00:31:19,880 --> 00:31:22,000
You'll see me with the Doctor,
the other me.

582
00:31:22,080 --> 00:31:25,000
The exactly the same, other me. Okay?

583
00:31:27,640 --> 00:31:28,640
-(BEEPING)
-(CLARA CLEARING THROAT)

584
00:31:32,560 --> 00:31:35,600
Afternoon. Thanks for keeping
out of my way.

585
00:31:36,560 --> 00:31:38,760
You haven't brought Dave with you,
I hope.

586
00:31:39,760 --> 00:31:42,600
His name's Danny. And no, I haven't.

587
00:31:44,040 --> 00:31:47,040
I've, uh, explained it all to him.
He gets it, he took it really well.

588
00:31:47,120 --> 00:31:48,440
Pass me that synestic.

589
00:31:53,720 --> 00:31:56,680
So, when the Blitzer comes back,
are you going to catch him with that?

590
00:31:56,880 --> 00:32:00,640
It'll be a long and fiddly job.
It's going to take me at least 24 hours.

591
00:32:00,720 --> 00:32:03,080
Even longer if people keep talking
to me, so do keep going.

592
00:32:03,160 --> 00:32:05,160
So, if it comes back Thursday night,
are you sure about that?

593
00:32:05,240 --> 00:32:06,440
'Cause you said chronodyne is unstable.

594
00:32:06,520 --> 00:32:08,880
If you want bother someone,
go and bother PE.

595
00:32:10,840 --> 00:32:12,240
He's a maths teacher.

596
00:32:13,120 --> 00:32:15,920
-That's a shame, I like maths.
-Not a soldier.

597
00:32:21,960 --> 00:32:23,800
Interesting.

598
00:32:24,880 --> 00:32:26,120
What is?

599
00:32:26,680 --> 00:32:28,320
I'm bored.

600
00:32:28,400 --> 00:32:30,240
Let's go somewhere fun,
what do you say?

601
00:32:30,360 --> 00:32:33,560
Do you want to see the Thames
frozen over? Oh, those frost fairs!

602
00:32:33,640 --> 00:32:35,120
You can't. The Skovox thing.

603
00:32:35,200 --> 00:32:36,200
It's a time machine.

604
00:32:36,280 --> 00:32:38,440
We can get back straightaway,
like we always do on your dates.

605
00:32:38,520 --> 00:32:41,840
Just make sure you don't get yourself
a tan or anything, or lose a limb.

606
00:32:41,920 --> 00:32:43,200
I don't think we should, not this time.

607
00:32:43,280 --> 00:32:45,960
You've never said no before.
Not even in the middle of dinner.

608
00:32:46,040 --> 00:32:47,800
Remember you had to eat
two meals in a row?

609
00:32:47,880 --> 00:32:50,720
I just think,
with the school in danger...

610
00:32:50,800 --> 00:32:51,800
(BEEPING)

611
00:32:51,960 --> 00:32:53,920
-Danny! Why are you...
-He already knows I'm here.

612
00:32:54,000 --> 00:32:56,440
That's why he's talking like that.
He's being clever.

613
00:32:57,640 --> 00:32:59,400
Now you mentioned it, being a Time Lord,

614
00:32:59,480 --> 00:33:02,600
I can feel a light-shield aura
when it's right next to me.

615
00:33:02,680 --> 00:33:05,440
Time Lord! Might have known.

616
00:33:05,520 --> 00:33:07,480
Might have known what?

617
00:33:07,560 --> 00:33:10,080
Well, the accent's good but you can
always spot the aristocracy.

618
00:33:10,160 --> 00:33:13,240
-It's in their... The attitude?
-Danny!

619
00:33:13,400 --> 00:33:15,480
Now, um, Time Lords,
do you salute those?

620
00:33:15,560 --> 00:33:17,720
-Definitely not.
-(SCOFFS) Sir!

621
00:33:18,280 --> 00:33:19,760
And you do not call me sir.

622
00:33:19,840 --> 00:33:21,960
As you wish, sir! Absolutely, sir!

623
00:33:22,280 --> 00:33:25,800
-And you can get out of my Tardis!
-Immediately, sir.

624
00:33:25,880 --> 00:33:27,840
Doctor, this is stupid, this is unfair!

625
00:33:27,920 --> 00:33:32,040
One thing, Clara. I'm a soldier,
guilty as charged. You see him?

626
00:33:32,120 --> 00:33:33,760
-He's an officer.
-I am not an officer!

627
00:33:33,840 --> 00:33:36,080
I'm the one who
carries you out of the fire.

628
00:33:36,160 --> 00:33:37,960
-He's the one who lights it.
-Out. Now.

629
00:33:38,040 --> 00:33:39,600
-Right away, sir? Straight now?
-Yes.

630
00:33:39,680 --> 00:33:42,120
-Am I dismissed?
-(SHOUTING) Yes, you are!

631
00:33:43,840 --> 00:33:44,840
That's him.

632
00:33:45,320 --> 00:33:46,880
Look at him right now.

633
00:33:47,400 --> 00:33:48,720
That's who he is.

634
00:33:54,640 --> 00:33:56,800
On balance,
I think that went quite well.

635
00:34:06,280 --> 00:34:08,800
Danny, it's not time to go home yet.

636
00:34:08,880 --> 00:34:10,640
It's parents' evening.

637
00:34:14,160 --> 00:34:15,440
Humans.

638
00:34:16,080 --> 00:34:17,800
I never learn.

639
00:34:18,120 --> 00:34:19,520
COURTNEY: What's in the box?

640
00:34:21,840 --> 00:34:23,840
It's not really a policeman, is it?

641
00:34:27,320 --> 00:34:31,360
You want to know what's in that box?
I'll tell you what's in that box.

642
00:34:32,160 --> 00:34:33,800
It's a time machine.

643
00:34:34,040 --> 00:34:36,240
It also travels in space

644
00:34:36,320 --> 00:34:39,560
and it usually contains a man
who just wants to get on with his work

645
00:34:39,640 --> 00:34:42,520
of preventing the end of the world

646
00:34:42,600 --> 00:34:45,640
but keeps being interrupted
by boring little humans.

647
00:34:46,200 --> 00:34:49,360
Cool. So, that's really a spaceship?

648
00:34:50,800 --> 00:34:53,160
I'm serious,
I'm trying to save this planet.

649
00:34:53,240 --> 00:34:56,760
End of the world for me tonight,
whatever you do. Parents' evening.

650
00:34:56,840 --> 00:34:59,040
Is your name really
Disruptive Influence?

651
00:34:59,560 --> 00:35:02,640
Courtney Woods. Can I go in space?

652
00:35:02,880 --> 00:35:05,440
I'll let you know.
I may have a vacancy.

653
00:35:05,600 --> 00:35:07,280
But not right now.

654
00:35:10,520 --> 00:35:13,480
Two days. I can do it.

655
00:35:15,520 --> 00:35:16,520
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

656
00:35:19,360 --> 00:35:24,200
Rights, are we quorate?
Time to admit the hordes.

657
00:35:24,280 --> 00:35:26,600
And look who's
at the front of the queue.

658
00:35:26,680 --> 00:35:28,760
-Who are they?
-CLARA: Courtney Woods' mum and dad.

659
00:35:28,840 --> 00:35:29,840
Can someone else do them first?

660
00:35:29,920 --> 00:35:31,600
No problem, Ade.
I can cope with anything tonight.

661
00:35:31,680 --> 00:35:33,280
Oh, happy days!

662
00:35:41,520 --> 00:35:42,520
(RUMBLING)

663
00:35:51,440 --> 00:35:52,440
(BEEPING)

664
00:35:59,960 --> 00:36:00,960
(RHYTHMIC BEEPING)

665
00:36:08,600 --> 00:36:12,280
No, no, no. No, no, no, no!

666
00:36:12,360 --> 00:36:16,400
I would say yes, I'm afraid Courtney
is a disruptive influence.

667
00:36:16,480 --> 00:36:19,480
Yeah, but last year you said
she was a very disruptive influence.

668
00:36:19,560 --> 00:36:22,280
So, I suppose that counts
as an improvement.

669
00:36:26,000 --> 00:36:27,000
(CLEARING THROAT)

670
00:36:30,520 --> 00:36:33,480
DANNY: Excuse me, I think
the caretaker wants me.

671
00:36:33,560 --> 00:36:36,760
Sorry, Mrs Christopholou,
I think the caretaker wants me, too.

672
00:36:36,840 --> 00:36:38,080
What about my Angelina?

673
00:36:38,160 --> 00:36:40,360
Yeah, she's great, yeah,
a really great girl, A-plus,

674
00:36:40,440 --> 00:36:42,800
ten out of ten,
top of the class. Sorry.

675
00:36:43,680 --> 00:36:46,560
Although, actually,
handwriting could be better.

676
00:36:51,120 --> 00:36:52,960
I'm sure they'll be back in a moment.

677
00:36:53,080 --> 00:36:55,480
Looks like our Courtney
was right about those two.

678
00:36:56,080 --> 00:36:58,640
-What's happening?
-Clara, the vortex is opening.

679
00:36:58,720 --> 00:37:00,600
You said Thursday night.
Right, hall, quick.

680
00:37:00,680 --> 00:37:02,080
PE, shut up.

681
00:37:02,320 --> 00:37:03,960
Clara, it'll scan the area,

682
00:37:04,040 --> 00:37:05,840
if it gets to parents' evening,
it'll kill them all.

683
00:37:05,920 --> 00:37:08,320
-We've got to evacuate.
-(SHOUTING) Shut up!

684
00:37:08,400 --> 00:37:09,880
Quickly. What do I do?

685
00:37:11,960 --> 00:37:14,000
It'll be here any second.
Get to the hall.

686
00:37:14,120 --> 00:37:16,960
Give it some squirts of
helicon energy, setting number 41,

687
00:37:17,040 --> 00:37:19,320
no more than three seconds each,
random pulses.

688
00:37:19,400 --> 00:37:22,280
Distract it, then you lead it away
from the hall, give me two minutes.

689
00:37:22,360 --> 00:37:24,280
-Then what?
-Just run straight to the Tardis.

690
00:37:24,360 --> 00:37:26,760
But your gadget isn't ready yet.
Twenty-four hours, you said.

691
00:37:26,840 --> 00:37:30,080
Yes, well, I've revised that down to
two minutes. Probably. Clara, go.

692
00:37:30,160 --> 00:37:32,000
-On my way.
-You're using her like a decoy?

693
00:37:32,080 --> 00:37:34,320
No, not like a decoy. As a decoy.

694
00:37:34,440 --> 00:37:36,760
Don't they teach you anything
at stupid school?

695
00:37:37,120 --> 00:37:38,800
Well, is there anything I can do?

696
00:37:38,880 --> 00:37:41,600
Yes. Yes, and this is very,
very important.

697
00:37:41,680 --> 00:37:42,840
Leave us alone!

698
00:37:47,560 --> 00:37:50,960
BLITZER: Disrupt temporal lock.
Disengage scan.

699
00:37:51,040 --> 00:37:52,040
Here we go.

700
00:37:52,160 --> 00:37:54,200
-(LOUD RUMBLING)
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

701
00:37:56,120 --> 00:38:01,160
BLITZER: Incoming, stop. Identified,
helicon. Helicon. Commence retargeting.

702
00:38:05,240 --> 00:38:07,840
BUTZER: Target acquired. Destroy.

703
00:38:13,800 --> 00:38:15,320
Target within range.

704
00:38:17,520 --> 00:38:20,840
Problem. Solution: destroy.

705
00:38:20,920 --> 00:38:21,920
(EXPLOSION)

706
00:38:23,320 --> 00:38:26,440
-Destroy. Destroy.
-Doctor, now, it's got to be now!

707
00:38:26,520 --> 00:38:27,640
Twenty seconds.

708
00:38:27,720 --> 00:38:29,080
Destroy. Destroy.

709
00:38:29,520 --> 00:38:30,600
Doctor!

710
00:38:33,520 --> 00:38:34,520
(SCREAMING)

711
00:38:37,160 --> 00:38:39,040
-Am I green? Am I green?
-You're green!

712
00:38:39,120 --> 00:38:40,840
Stop! Skovox Blitzer!

713
00:38:40,920 --> 00:38:41,920
Awaiting orders.

714
00:38:42,000 --> 00:38:45,960
Superior Skovox Artificer.
Analyse, stop. Analyse, stop.

715
00:38:46,040 --> 00:38:51,240
BLITZER: Superior recognised.
Pattern, 1-7-0. Orders. Orders.

716
00:38:51,880 --> 00:38:53,160
Why's it listening to you?

717
00:38:53,240 --> 00:38:55,920
Listening to its superior.
This is a rough copy.

718
00:38:56,000 --> 00:38:57,000
It thinks I'm its general.

719
00:38:57,080 --> 00:39:00,200
Initiate input.
Commence shutdown protocol.

720
00:39:00,560 --> 00:39:02,360
No conflict. Conclusion?

721
00:39:02,960 --> 00:39:04,680
BLITZER: Problem. Solution.

722
00:39:06,080 --> 00:39:07,080
Conclusion?

723
00:39:07,200 --> 00:39:10,040
BLITZER: Final input code missing.
Emergency terminate.

724
00:39:10,120 --> 00:39:12,560
Initiate self-destruct in nine, eight...

725
00:39:12,640 --> 00:39:14,600
The input code.
I forgot the final input code!

726
00:39:14,680 --> 00:39:15,960
BLITZER: ...seven, six, five...

727
00:39:16,080 --> 00:39:18,200
CLARA: Do it now!
DOCTOR: I need time. Distract it, Clara!

728
00:39:18,280 --> 00:39:20,400
CLARA: Me? What can I do?
BLITZER: ...three two, one...

729
00:39:20,480 --> 00:39:22,480
DANNY: Oi, Skovox, over here.

730
00:39:22,560 --> 00:39:23,560
(BEEPING)

731
00:39:24,080 --> 00:39:25,880
BLITZER: Under attack.

732
00:39:29,880 --> 00:39:30,880
(GLASS SHATTERING)

733
00:39:30,960 --> 00:39:36,680
Artificer. Artificer. Stop. Confirm.
Override final input code.

734
00:39:36,760 --> 00:39:39,640
BLITZER: Code accepted.
Abort self-destruct.

735
00:39:40,880 --> 00:39:44,320
Orders accepted. Stop. Stop. Stop.

736
00:39:46,000 --> 00:39:49,000
(CHUCKLING) Oh, my God!
Oh, my God, you were amazing!

737
00:39:49,080 --> 00:39:51,120
Oh, my God, you were so brilliant!

738
00:39:51,200 --> 00:39:53,840
Well, yeah, I was okay,
wasn't I? (CHUCKLING)

739
00:39:54,320 --> 00:39:57,120
I was behind you every step of the way.

740
00:39:57,440 --> 00:39:59,440
Had to make sure you were safe.

741
00:40:00,520 --> 00:40:01,560
You okay?

742
00:40:03,600 --> 00:40:04,640
Okay.

743
00:40:06,360 --> 00:40:07,640
Just okay?

744
00:40:08,800 --> 00:40:10,400
DANNY: It's all right,
it doesn't matter.

745
00:40:10,480 --> 00:40:12,600
I don't need him to like me.

746
00:40:12,760 --> 00:40:15,200
It doesn't matter
if he likes me or hates me.

747
00:40:15,280 --> 00:40:18,280
I just need to do
exactly one thing for you.

748
00:40:18,520 --> 00:40:21,520
Doctor, am I right?

749
00:40:24,000 --> 00:40:25,080
Yes.

750
00:40:25,800 --> 00:40:27,760
What? What one thing?

751
00:40:28,880 --> 00:40:30,600
I need to be good enough for you.

752
00:40:31,320 --> 00:40:34,040
That's why he's angry.
Just in case I'm not.

753
00:40:40,920 --> 00:40:43,920
He, uh...
He did just save the whole world.

754
00:40:45,520 --> 00:40:47,120
DOCTOR: Yeah, yeah.

755
00:40:49,280 --> 00:40:50,320
Good start.

756
00:40:55,080 --> 00:40:58,080
Farewell, Skovox Blitzer.
Have a nice war.

757
00:40:58,200 --> 00:41:01,400
So, Courtney Woods, impressed yet?

758
00:41:02,560 --> 00:41:05,440
Actually, I'm feeling a bit ill.

759
00:41:05,520 --> 00:41:07,800
Ah, it can be a bit overwhelming.

760
00:41:08,240 --> 00:41:11,920
But look, the Olveron Cluster.

761
00:41:12,600 --> 00:41:17,360
A million stars,
100 million inhabited planets.

762
00:41:17,880 --> 00:41:18,880
(RETCHING)

763
00:41:21,440 --> 00:41:22,920
(VOMITING)

764
00:41:23,360 --> 00:41:26,600
Ah, yes, there has been a spillage.

765
00:41:31,400 --> 00:41:33,160
(CHATTER ON TELEVISION)

766
00:41:34,120 --> 00:41:36,040
So what do you think of him now?

767
00:41:36,760 --> 00:41:38,360
-Of the Doctor?
-Yeah.

768
00:41:39,520 --> 00:41:42,000
See, he's all right, isn't he, really?
Underneath it all.

769
00:41:46,960 --> 00:41:47,960
(TURNING TELEVISION OFF)

770
00:41:48,600 --> 00:41:49,640
Okay.

771
00:41:49,800 --> 00:41:51,120
Tell me what you're thinking.

772
00:41:53,920 --> 00:41:55,240
I know men like him.

773
00:41:55,600 --> 00:41:57,120
I've served under them.

774
00:41:58,040 --> 00:42:01,960
They push you and make you stronger,

775
00:42:02,560 --> 00:42:05,200
till you're doing things
you never thought you could.

776
00:42:05,640 --> 00:42:09,040
I saw you tonight,
you did exactly what he told you.

777
00:42:09,160 --> 00:42:10,760
You weren't even scared.

778
00:42:13,120 --> 00:42:14,280
And you should have been.

779
00:42:16,720 --> 00:42:20,120
I trust him. He has never let me down.

780
00:42:24,040 --> 00:42:25,560
Fine.

781
00:42:27,600 --> 00:42:30,720
If he ever pushes you too far,
I want you to tell me

782
00:42:30,800 --> 00:42:32,200
because I know what that's like.

783
00:42:33,840 --> 00:42:36,960
-You'll tell me if that happens, yeah?
-Yeah, it's a deal.

784
00:42:37,040 --> 00:42:40,040
-No. It's a promise.
-Okay, I promise.

785
00:42:41,880 --> 00:42:44,160
And if you break that promise, Clara,
we're finished.

786
00:42:44,240 --> 00:42:45,240
Don't say that.

787
00:42:45,320 --> 00:42:48,720
I am saying it because
if you don't tell me the truth,

788
00:42:48,800 --> 00:42:53,160
I can't help you and I could never
stand not being able to help you.

789
00:42:54,200 --> 00:42:55,240
Are we clear?

790
00:42:56,560 --> 00:42:59,240
Yes. We're clear.

791
00:43:04,760 --> 00:43:06,240
(TURNING TELEVISION ON)

792
00:43:12,880 --> 00:43:16,320
It was mad, it was like in a film
or on the telly,

793
00:43:16,400 --> 00:43:19,000
like with science fiction guns.

794
00:43:19,120 --> 00:43:22,120
Skovox Blitzer, sounds like.
We've had a few in from that.

795
00:43:22,200 --> 00:43:24,280
-Wouldn't feel too bad.
-If I hadn't...

796
00:43:26,360 --> 00:43:28,280
If I hadn't...

797
00:43:29,240 --> 00:43:33,200
Hang on. That doesn't make sense.

798
00:43:34,160 --> 00:43:35,440
Makes perfect sense to me.

799
00:43:35,560 --> 00:43:40,120
How did I escape?
I don't remember how I got away.

800
00:43:40,200 --> 00:43:44,840
Well, I was coming to that.
I'm afraid you really rather didn't.

801
00:43:49,600 --> 00:43:50,600
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

802
00:43:51,440 --> 00:43:53,040
Then how did I get here?

803
00:43:53,160 --> 00:43:55,440
Well, big question.

804
00:43:55,520 --> 00:43:56,600
Where am I?

805
00:43:56,720 --> 00:43:59,280
What name would you like?
There's a range. The afterlife.

806
00:43:59,360 --> 00:44:02,080
The Promised Land.
I'm partial to the Nethersphere.

807
00:44:06,720 --> 00:44:08,720
My God!

808
00:44:16,920 --> 00:44:19,560
Sorry, she's a bit, uh, busy today.

809
00:44:20,840 --> 00:44:23,840
So, any questions?

810
00:44:26,360 --> 00:44:29,280
CLARA: Hello, Earth.
We have a terrible decision to make.

811
00:44:29,360 --> 00:44:32,480
An innocent life versus
the future of all mankind.

812
00:44:32,920 --> 00:44:34,920
DOCTOR: Whatever future
humanity might have

813
00:44:35,000 --> 00:44:38,200
depends upon the choice that is made
right here, right now.

814
00:44:38,560 --> 00:44:40,360
-(DOCTOR SCREAMING)
-(ALIEN SCREECHING)

815
00:44:41,680 --> 00:44:42,680
(BEEPING)

816
00:44:43,360 --> 00:44:44,560
Decision made.

817
00:44:44,800 --> 00:44:46,040
(SCREECHING)

